In preparation of our treatment of self-coherent DPSK detection, let us first review conventional differential phase detection in a slightly generalized form referred to here as polyphase DPSK (P-DPSK). This variant of DPSK increases the delay in the differential encoder of the DPSK transmitter (TX), as well as in the receiver (RX) processing, from \( \overline{I}_{d} \) to \( \sum_{i} d^{2}T_{d} \), where \( T_{d} \) is the symbol duration (i.e., the symbol or band rate in \( T_{d}^{2} \)), and the called polyphase period, its inverse \( \overline{I}^{*} \) is called the polyphase rate, and \( d \) is an integer called interleaving factor. Possible motivations for conventional P-DPSK [20]-[24] include:<|txt_split|>i) enabling polarization alternation or interleaving, whereby adjacent symbols are transmitted with orthogonal alternating polarizations, e.g., all even samples are \(x\)-polarized, whereas all odd samples are \(y\)-polarized to reduce the nonlinear intrachannel FWM and XPM penalty due to XPM-induced nonlinear polarization rotation;<|txt_split|>ii) to allow polarization multiplexing of two independent (even and odd) DPSK streams;<|txt_split|>iii) to enable optical time-division multiplexing of DPSK modulated streams.<|txt_split|>Our main motivation for adopting polyphase operation is different (though, as a side benefit, we should be able to accommodate the objectives above as well): we aim to ease the \( \mathrm{DF} \) delay in the process of making past decisions to be fed back in a timely manner (Section IV).<|txt_split|>Establishing our notation, let discrete-time samples at the band rate \( T_{\mathrm{m}}^{-1} \) be indexed by brackets, e.g., \( [q_k^{-1}, - 1] \), \( [q_k^{\prime \prime}] \) are taken \( T_{\mathrm{s}}^{2} \) seconds apart, whereas samples taken at the slower polyphase rate \( T^{-1} \) are indexed by subscripts, e.g., \( A_{\mathrm{M}k}^{-1},A_{\mathrm{M}}^{-1} \) are taken \( T = dT_{\mathrm{s}}^{2} \) apart. Evidently, there are \( d \) distinct subsequences interleaved at the polyphase rate<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {A} _ {n} = \tilde {A} [ n d + i ], i = 0, 1, \dots , d - 1. \tag {1}
\]<|txt_split|>We distinguish between real and complex samples by denoting the complex samples by overtildes. The differential precoder in the P-DSPK transmitter is then modeled as a multiplicative accumulator over the \( M \)-ary PSK constellation<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {a} _ {k} = \tilde {a} _ {k - 1} \tilde {s} _ {k} \Leftrightarrow \mu_ {k} = \mu_ {k - 1} + \Delta \mu_ {k} \tag {2}
\]<|txt_split|>where \(\mu_{k}\) are the transmitted phases, \(\hat{Q}_{k} \equiv e^{j\Phi_{k}}\) are called angular states, and \(\hat{B}_{k} \equiv e^{i2\Phi_{k}}\) are called rotation symbols, viewed as the information symbols mapped by the transmitted phase. The \(M\) -PSK constellation is constructed along with the phases \(\mu_{k}\) out of a M-PSK constellation<|txt_split|>\[
\mu_ {0}, \Delta \mu_ {0} \in \left\{\frac {2 \pi m}{M} \right\} _ {m = 0} ^ {M - 1}, \hat {\alpha} _ {0}, \hat {\eta} _ {0} \in \{e ^ {2 \pi m, \Delta t} \} _ {m = 0} ^ {M - 1}. (3)
\]<|txt_split|>The differential precoder generates the current angular state \(\delta_{\mathrm{R}}\) by multiplicatively applying the rotation symbol \(\delta_{\mathrm{R}}\) onto the previous angular state, \(\delta_{\mathrm{P - R}}\), e.g., for \(d = 2\) the differential phase of the current is computed. The differential precoder has a broad interval (with an obvious generalization for \(d\) polyphases).<|txt_split|>\[
\delta [ 2 n ] = \delta [ 2 n - 2 ] \delta_ {2 n}, \quad \delta [ 2 n + 1 ] = \delta [ 2 n - 1 ] \delta_ {2 n + 1}. \tag {4}
\]<|txt_split|>The transmitted symbol is then simply a scaled version of the angular state \(\hat{A}_k = A_k\hat{q}_k\) with \(A_{\mathrm{k}}\) the optical carrier amplitude. We also introduce a cumulative rotation increment over an interval \([k - m_k,k - 1]\) of duration \((n - 1)\bar{T}\)<|txt_split|>\[
\delta_ {[ m - n, k - 1 ]} \equiv \delta_ {m + n + 1} \delta_ {m + n + 2}, \delta_ {m - 1} = \prod_ {k = 0} ^ {n - 1} \delta_ {m - n + k} (5)
\]<|txt_split|>rotating from the initial to the final transmitted phasors<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {A} _ {k - 1} = \tilde {A} _ {k - m} \tilde {s} _ {[ k - m, k - 1 ]}. \tag {6}
\]<|txt_split|>The effective discrete-time optical channel from the TX to the optically preamplified samples at the RX input is modeled as \( \hat{h}_{\mathrm{RX}} = \frac{\lambda_{\mathrm{RX}}\sigma^{\mathrm{rx}}}{2} + \hat{h}_{\mathrm{RL}} \) where \( \hat{h}_{\mathrm{RL}} \) is amplified spontaneous noise (ASE)-induced circular Gaussian additive noise of variance \( 2\sigma^2 \) and \( \varphi_{\mathrm{R}} \) represents the phase noise (PN) accrued by each sample. The effective discrete-time signal is the source (laser PS) or nonlinear SMP- or XMP-induced PN.<|txt_split|>The noise processes \( \mathcal{P}_k \) and \( \mathcal{A}_k \) are assumed to be independent, i.e., \( \mathcal{P}_k = 0 \), \( \mathcal{A}_k = 1 \). The input channel, \( \varphi_k = 0 \sim 1 / \sqrt{n} [f(\frac{2\pi}{N})] \), i.e. \( \mathcal{P}_k = -\lambda_{\mathrm{ref}} e^{i\theta} + \mathcal{P}_k \).<|txt_split|>The maximum likelihood (ML) decision (optimal over a linear channel) at the RX is described by<|txt_split|>\[
\hat {\alpha} = \operatorname {a r g m a x} _ {k} u _ {k} ^ {(\alpha)} \tag {7}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
w _ {k} ^ {(\alpha)} \equiv \mathrm {R e} \left\{\hat {\gamma} _ {k} \hat {\gamma} _ {k - 1} ^ {\dagger} e ^ {- j \Delta_ {k} / \epsilon^ {(\alpha)}} \right\} = \mathrm {R e} \left\{\hat {\gamma} _ {k} \hat {\gamma} _ {k} ^ {(\alpha) *} \right\}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
= | \hat {p} _ {k} | | \hat {p} _ {k - 1} | \cos \left(\angle \hat {p} _ {k} - \angle \hat {p} _ {k - 1} - \Delta \psi_ {k} ^ {(a)}\right) \tag {8}
\]<|txt_split|>where \(\alpha\) is the transmission index. The sufficient statistic \(\hat{p}_{\mathrm{R}}^{\mathrm{F}\alpha -1}\) is optically generated in the RX interferometric front end (IFE). Generally denote by \(\mathrm{Diff}[\eta ,\gamma ]\) an asymmetric Mach-Zehnder (MZ) balanced detection-DI [25] with relative phase bias \(\gamma\) between the two arms and relative delay \(\eta I^2\) (the multipole \(T\) ) to be later fitted for utility symbol detection. The electrical output of such device at discrete time \(k_{s}\) in response to an input field sample \(\hat{p}_{\mathrm{R}}\) is expressed up to a constant as<|txt_split|>\[
\left. \tilde {d} _ {m} ^ {\gamma \gamma} e ^ {r _ {n}} [ k ] \equiv \operatorname {R e} \left\{\tilde {r} _ {n} \tilde {r} _ {- m} ^ {*} e ^ {j \gamma} \right\}, \right. \tag {9}
\]<|txt_split|>Similarly, the output of a DI biased in quadrature is expressed as<|txt_split|>\[
\hat {\eta} _ {m \ell} ^ {\sigma , - \tau / 2} [ k ] = \mathrm {R e} \left\{\hat {r} _ {\ell} \hat {\eta} _ {m - m} ^ {\sigma} e ^ {\beta_ {\ell} \cdot - \tau / 2} \right\}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
= \operatorname {I m} \left\{\tilde {r} _ {k} \hat {r} _ {m - n} ^ {*} e ^ {\mathrm {j} \varphi} \right\} = \hat {q} _ {m T} ^ {(\gamma) a m} [ k ] \tag {10}
\]<|txt_split|>where \(\mathrm{re}_{\mathrm{im}}\) denote real and imaginary parts and the pair of quadrature Dls, defining a "complex Df" with output<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {q} _ {m \ell} ^ {(\gamma)} [ k ] \equiv \tilde {r} _ {k} \tilde {r} _ {k - m} ^ {*} e ^ {\tilde {r} \gamma}. \tag {11}
\]<|txt_split|>We adopt for brevity a notational convention often omitting the bias phase superscripts but the indication of nonzero. bias phases \(\gamma \neq 0\) by a prime, writing \(\mathbb{Z}_{\mathrm{max}}^{n}[\frac{1}{n}]\), with \(n = 2,3,\ldots ,6\) and \(n = 7,8,\ldots ,10\) respectively. The indices such as \(\mathbb{Z}_{\mathrm{max}}^{n}\) denote the output of a zero-phase-based DI.

The decision statistic (8) in the ML decoding law (7) may be equivalently expressed as<|txt_split|>\[
w _ {k} ^ {(\alpha)} \equiv \operatorname {R e} \left\{\tilde {q} _ {k} \tilde {s} _ {k} ^ {(\alpha) *} \right\} = \operatorname {R e} \left\{\tilde {q} _ {k} ^ {*} \tilde {s} _ {k} ^ {*} \right\} \tag {12}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {q} _ {k} \equiv q _ {T} [ k ]
\]<|txt_split|>\[
\equiv \tilde {t} _ {h} \tilde {r} _ {h - 1} ^ {\prime \prime}, \tilde {u} _ {h} \equiv e ^ {c ^ {p / 2} \tilde {q} _ {h}} = e ^ {c ^ {p / 2} \tilde {t} _ {h}} \tilde {r} _ {h - 1} ^ {\prime \prime} = q _ {h} ^ {\mathrm {e v}} + \mu_ {h} ^ {\mathrm {e v}} \tag {m.12}
\]<|txt_split|>Here \( \hat{B}_{\mathrm{ij}}^{\mathrm{e}} = \frac{\beta_{\mathrm{ij}}}{2}\mathrm{e}^{i / 4}\varepsilon \in (\pm 1,\pm j)\sqrt{2} \) are rotation symbols in a \( 45^{\circ} \) tilted QPSK constellation with the transmission index \( \alpha \) discarded off \( \hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ij}}^{\mathrm{e}} \). The decoding is then formulated as maximization of \( \sum_{j = 1}^{N}\hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ij}}^{\mathrm{e}} \), where \( \hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ij}}^{\mathrm{e}} \) is the maximum, reducing to decision on the signs of the re-im parts of \( \hat{Q}_{\mathrm{ij}}^{\mathrm{e}} \).<|txt_split|>\[
\hat {S} _ {k} ^ {\prime} = \frac {\left[ \operatorname {g a m m a} _ {k} ^ {H} u _ {k} ^ {H} e ^ {- j} + \operatorname {g a m m a} _ {k} ^ {H} u _ {k} ^ {H} e ^ {j k \pi} \right]}{\sqrt {2}}, \tag {13}
\]<|txt_split|>The decision variables \(q_{\mathrm{m}}^{(n)}, q_{\mathrm{m}}^{(\mathrm{off})}\) are interferometrically generated by the phase-biased system, and the phase-biased \(T\) is set at \(\pm 45^{\circ}\), with delay \(T\) equal to the polyphase period.<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {q} _ {r} ^ {\tau} [ k ] = \mathrm {R e} \left\{\tilde {r} _ {k} \tilde {r} _ {k - 1} ^ {\tau} e ^ {j \pi / 4} \right\}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {q} _ {t} ^ {m} [ k ] = \mathrm {R e} \left\{\tilde {r} _ {k} \tilde {r} _ {k - 1} ^ {*} e ^ {- j \pi / 4} \right\}. \tag {14}
\]

