The principle of operation, briefly introduced in [2] for DF-aided MS-BDPSK, is now reviewed and extended to \(M\)-ary DPSK. Synthetic LO generation is interpreted in terms of estimation theory as well as intuitively accounting for it in terms of a phase-noise reduction effect due to averaging independent noise. The proposed approach is based on the assumption that the noise are the phase constellation size \(M\) (in particular, \(M = 2\) for DBPSK and \(M = 4\) for DQPSK) and \(D\), the multisymbol sliding window size in chips, with the fifth roughest chip representing the "signal" while the preceding \(D - 1\) chips, ranging from \(k - D + 1\) to \(k - 1\), are used to synthesize the improved reference (ref). As receive complexity rises upon increasing the number of parameters, we typically consider \(M = 2, 4, 8, \ldots\), i.e., DBPSK, DQPSK, or DPPS. For simplicity, we assume that \(D = 3, 4, 5\) chips. Notice that \(D = 2\) designates conventional DPSK to be henceforth referred to as two-symbol DPSK (2S-DPSK).<|txt_split|>As discussed in [2] and [3], the noise variance of the DPSK phase difference decision statistic is the sum of PN variances of the two adjacent symbols—the information and reference have been extracted from the PDSK signal. The PDSK is divided by about \(3\mathrm{dB}\) relative to homodyne PSK, as it reduces to \(2.4\mathrm{dB}\) at bit error rate (BER) of \(10^{-3}\) due to the degrading effect of amplitude noise on PSK. In principle, if a precise estimate of the phase of the last symbol reference were available, the DPSK performance would coincide with that of coherent homodyne PSK since the variance of the PN difference would be less than unity. This is not the case for the PDSK, which is considered perfect. By feeding back the previous, mostly correctly decoded, signals, a better phase reference is extracted and effectively used to reduce the PN of the previous (reference) symbol. In essence, the estimate of the phase reference symbol, generated out of previous observations and decision feedback, better than the PN reference symbol, can be obtained by combining the estimation operation. These intuitive statements may be rigorously formalized by applying estimation theory to derive an ML estimate \(\hat{\Delta}_{\mathrm{ML}}^{\mathrm{opt}}\) of the ideal noiseless reference \(\hat{\Delta}_{\mathrm{ML}}^{\mathrm{opt}}\) as a function of the vector of past observations \(\left[\hat{h}_{\mathrm{p - D + 1}},\dots ,\hat{h}_{\mathrm{p - 2}},\hat{h}_{\mathrm{p - 1}}\right]\), assuming the linear channel model \(\hat{h}_{\mathrm{p}} = \hat{A}_{\mathrm{p}}\hat{e}^{i\omega t} + i\hat{k}_{\mathrm{p}}\). Using the recursive rotation relation (6) and the fact that the noise is additive white noise, the ML estimate comes out as a linear combination of past observations, with coefficients given by the respective rotations<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {A} _ {k - 1} \equiv \tilde {H} _ {k - 1} = \sum_ {m = 1} ^ {k - 1} \tilde {\rho} _ {(m, n - k - 1) j} ^ {k} \tilde {\rho} _ {- m - n}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
= \hat {r} _ {k - 1} + \hat {s} _ {k - 1} \hat {r} _ {k - 2} + \hat {s} _ {k - 1} \hat {s} _ {k - 2} \hat {r} _ {k - 3}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
+ \dots + \hat {s} _ {k - 1} \hat {s} _ {k - 2} \dots \hat {s} _ {k - D + 2} \hat {r} _ {k - D + 1}. \tag {16}
\]<|txt_split|>Actually this estimate should have been expressed in terms of the past transmitted rotation symbols \(\{\hat{S}_{\mathrm{m}}\}_{\mathrm{m} = 1}^{\infty}\) (without hat) to which the RX does not have access; however, the RX reorts instead to the slicer estimates \(\{\hat{S}_{\mathrm{m}}\}_{\mathrm{m} = 1}^{\infty}\) representing<|txt_contd|>the past decisions, which coincide as with the transmitted rotation symbols \(\delta_{\mathrm{m - m}} = \delta_{\mathrm{m - m}}\) as long as the decisions are correct. The error propagation impact of incorrect decisions was shown both theoretically [2] and in simulations [2], [19] to be small.<|txt_split|>The estimate \( \widehat{R}_{\widehat{H} -1} \) may be viewed as an improved reference or a synthetic self-coherent LO, generated in terms of prior observations and prior decisions and fed back to generate the improved reference. The angle \( z \widehat{R}_{\widehat{H} -1} \) provides a better phase reference than \( \delta \widehat{r}_{\widehat{H} -1} \) (the noisy phase of the previous chip, which is not available at the time of the first DFS). For intuitive insight into the reference improvement, first specialize to 2S-DFSK \( (D = 2) \), in which case \( \widehat{R}_{\widehat{H} -1} = \widehat{r}_{\widehat{H} -1} \), i.e., the estimate simply reduces to the last reference symbol.<|txt_split|>Next consider \( D = 3 \), in which case \( \tilde{R}_{k - 1} = \tilde{r}_{k - 1} + \tilde{r}_{k - 1} - 2 \).<|txt_split|>In the noiseless case, we set \(\hat{n}_k = 0\), i.e., \(\tilde{r}_k = \tilde{A}_k = \langle \tilde{r}_k \rangle\), yielding for the noiseless estimate<|txt_split|>\[
\left\langle \hat {B} _ {k - 1} \right\rangle = \hat {A} _ {k - 1} + \hat {B} _ {k - 1} \hat {A} _ {k - 2} = \hat {A} _ {k - 1} + \hat {A} _ {k - 1} = 2 \hat {A} _ {k - 1}, \tag {17}
\]<|txt_split|>The mean of the improved reference has doubled in length, i.e., quadrupled in power. Its noise component is \( \hat{\eta}_{\mathrm{H1}} - \hat{\eta}_{\mathrm{H2}} + \hat{\eta}_{\mathrm{H3}} - 2 \), with double the variance relative to \( \hat{\eta}_{\mathrm{H1}} \), resulting in doubled \( \hat{\eta}_{\mathrm{R}} \). For general \( D \), the noises or mean value of the estimate is<|txt_split|>\[
\left\langle \hat {H} _ {k - n} \right\rangle = \sum_ {m = 1} ^ {k - 1} \prod_ {i = 1} ^ {n - 1} \delta_ {\mathbf {x} _ {i m - n}} \hat {\mathcal {E}} _ {k - m - i} = \sum_ {m = 1} ^ {k - 1} \delta_ {\mathbf {x} _ {(m, k - m)} (k - m)}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
= \sum_ {m = 1} ^ {D - 1} \tilde {A} _ {k - m, k - 1} \tilde {A} _ {k - m} = \sum_ {m = 1} ^ {D - 1} \tilde {A} _ {k - m} = (D - 1) \tilde {A} _ {k - 1}. \tag {18}
\]<|txt_split|>The \(D - 1\) identical mean-value phasors add up coherently, i.e., the signal amplitude component of the reference is coherently reinforced to \(D - 1\) times the noise phase \(\lambda_{\mathrm{ref}}(x)\) (the average phase of the reference is zero). The same phase of the received phasors \(\tilde{\varphi}_{\mathrm{ref}} = \tilde{\varphi}_{1} + \dots +\tilde{\varphi}_{N} + \tilde{\varphi}_{N + 1}\) are all rotated in approximate alignment with \(\tilde{\varphi}_{i}(x)\) (only perturbed by the PN); hence the signal amplitude is coherently reinforced to \(\mathcal{X}\geq D - 1\) whereas the noise contributions add up incoherently on a root mean square basis as \(\sqrt{D - 1}\), assuming uncorrelated successively between the two phases. The results show that the number of chips \(D - 1\) which take part in forming the improved reference, with \(\mathcal{A}_i\) the magnitude of the transmitted symbols, is<|txt_split|>\[
\operatorname {S N R} \left[ \tilde {R} _ {\mathrm {i n t}} - 1 \right] = \frac {\left| \left(\tilde {R} _ {\mathrm {i n t}} - 1\right) ^ {2} \right|}{\operatorname {V a r} \tilde {R} _ {\mathrm {i n t}}} = \frac {\left(A _ {n} (D - 1) ^ {2}\right)}{(D - 1) ^ {2} \lambda^ {2}}
