We consider systems with \( M > 2 \) for arbitrary \( M \). The IFE structure was already described in (25). The difference relative to DQPSK is that the main DIs are biased at \( \pi /M \) and \( \pi /M - \pi /2 \) rather than \( \pm \pi /4 \). For conventional \( (1) = 2 \) \( M \)-ary DPSK, such phase biases enable detecting \( M \)-ary DPSK with just the two quadrature DIs directly feeding a more complex slice performing \( M / 4 - 1 \) rotations of the IQ plane in the \( M / 4 - 1 \) direction. This is not possible in the case of a single principle does not change as a result of using the SC detection; however, in this case the slicer just described operates on the adiatively corrected outputs \( \tilde{q}_i^{ref} \), \( q_i^{ref0} \) of the two main DIs, with the corrections generated in the SP as before, by means of complex rotations of the auxiliary DI outputs according to the cumu<|txt_contd|>lative rotation symbols. Generalizing (34) to arbitrary \(M\), the spin operators \(\mathcal{S}_i\) are replaced by \(\pi / M\), yielding at SP output the re-inon parts as<|txt_split|>\[
\tilde {q} _ {k} ^ {\prime} = \tilde {q} ^ {\prime r e} + j \tilde {q} ^ {\prime i m} = e ^ {j \pi / M} \tilde {q} _ {k} = e ^ {j \pi / M} \tilde {r} _ {k} \tilde {R} _ {k - 1} ^ {*}
\]<|txt_split|>\[
= \hat {q} _ {T} ^ {\prime} [ k ] + e ^ {j \pi^ {A / I}} \hat {s} _ {k - 1} ^ {*} \hat {q} _ {2 T} [ k ]
\]<|txt_split|>\[
+ e ^ {i \pi / \Delta I} \delta_ {k = 2} ^ {*} \delta_ {k = 1} ^ {*} q _ {I T} [ k ] + \dots . \tag {37}
\]<|txt_split|>Unfortunately, as the rotation angle in each term is no longer \(\pi /4\), the real and imaginary parts are no longer bipolar; hence complex rotations cannot be simply performed by CCT devices. In fact, the complex rotation of a device with spinors (CMs) are required to perform multiplications of the form<|txt_split|>\[
\hat {y} (t) = y ^ {e} (t) + j y ^ {i n} (t) = e ^ {j 2 \pi / \Delta} \left(x ^ {r} (t) + j x ^ {i n} (t)\right) \tag {38}
\]<|txt_split|>for integer \( r \). Moreover, the QCRs in the DFL are to be replaced by more general \( M \)-ary constellation rotator (MCRs), representing multiplications within the group \( [\ell_{\mathrm{DFT}}^{2} / 3]_{\mathrm{M - R}}^{\mathrm{d}}, \) realizable as combinational circuits with larger truth tables. Upon relabelling \( C1 - C1 \) and QCR-MCR, the block diagrams, appearing in Figure 7, can be transformed into a series of \( M \)-ary multiplications over "as is" to the \( M \)-ary DPSK case. Unfortunately, the realization of CMs in the analog domain would be prohibitive. An alternative would be using high-speed analog-to-digital (A/D) conversion, performing the complex multiplications in the digital domain. However, assuming access to digital postprocessing, the postprocessing scheme of [7]-[11], based on an IFE implementation, can achieve roughly the same performance. Alternative approaches to self-coherent detection of \( M \)-ary DPSK, not requiring A/D conversion, are introduced in the next two sections.

